Bean scopes, and the bean lifecycle.

Every bean has a scope, which answers two questions: how many instances of it exist, and how long each one lives. The default scope, and by far the most common, is singleton: exactly one shared instance for the entire application context, created eagerly at startup. The next is prototype: a brand-new instance every single time someone asks for the bean. And web applications add two more, request, meaning one instance per H-T-T-P request, and session, meaning one per user session.

Singletons are the default for a good reason: your services are usually stateless, holding no per-user data, so a single shared instance is all you need. But there is a classic trap. If a singleton bean injects a prototype bean, the whole thing is still effectively a singleton, because that prototype is resolved exactly once, at the moment the singleton is constructed. If you genuinely need a fresh prototype on every call, you inject an object-provider of that type and ask it for a new one each time.

Now the lifecycle. After Spring constructs a bean and injects all its dependencies, it gives the bean two optional hooks. A method annotated at-post-construct runs once, after injection is complete, which is the right place for any setup that needs the injected fields to already be populated. And a method annotated at-pre-destroy runs when the context is shutting down, for cleanup. The full order is worth memorising: construct, then inject dependencies, then at-post-construct runs, then the bean is usable for the life of the app, then on shutdown at-pre-destroy runs.
